Here's the complete migration from ASP.NET Framework WebForms to ASP.NET Core 8 MVC, addressing all `Thread.Abort` patterns:

## Patterns Found

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | `btnExport_Click` | Return `FileContentResult` |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | `btnRedirect_Click` | Return `RedirectResult` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `btnRedirect_Click` | Remove entirely |
| Manual response writing | `btnExport_Click` | Use `File()` helper |

## Migrated Code (ASP.NET Core 8)

```csharp
public class ReportController : Controller
{
    private readonly ILogger<ReportController> _logger;

    public ReportController(ILogger<ReportController> logger)
    {
        _logger = logger;
    }

    // POST /Report/Export
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        // In ASP.NET Core, return a result object ‚Äî never write
        // directly to the response and call Response.End().
        var data = GenerateReport();
        var bytes = System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data);
        return File(bytes, "text/csv", "report.csv");
    }

    // POST /Report/Redirect
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult RedirectAction()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // Just return RedirectResult ‚Äî no Thread.Abort,
            // no endResponse parameter.
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // No catch (ThreadAbortException) ‚Äî it doesn't exist
        // in modern .NET and was never real error handling.
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            _logger.LogError(ex, "ProcessRequest failed");
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }

    private string GenerateReport() { /* ... */ return ""; }
    private void ProcessRequest() { /* ... */ }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls to Watch For

**1. `Response.End()` ‚Üí just return**
`Response.End()` called `Thread.Abort` internally. In ASP.NET Core, `Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. Return an `IActionResult` instead ‚Äî the framework handles the response lifecycle.

**2. `Response.Redirect(url, true)` ‚Üí `Redirect(url)`**
The `true` (endResponse) parameter triggered `Thread.Abort` to halt execution. In ASP.NET Core, `Redirect()` returns a result object ‚Äî execution flows naturally back to the framework. No abort needed.

**3. Remove `catch (ThreadAbortException)` entirely**
This catch existed only to swallow the exception thrown by `Response.Redirect(..., true)`. Since there's no `Thread.Abort` in .NET 8, this block is dead code. **Don't** replace it with `catch (OperationCanceledException)` ‚Äî that's for cancellation-token scenarios, not redirects.

**4. Null-safety on `User.Identity`**
In ASP.NET Core, `User.Identity` can be `null` when no authentication middleware has run. Use `?.IsAuthenticated ?? true` or the `[Authorize]` attribute.

**5. Don't write directly to `Response`**
The old pattern of `Response.Clear() ‚Üí Write ‚Üí End` is an anti-pattern in Core. Always return an `IActionResult`. If you need streaming for large files:

```csharp
[HttpPost]
public async Task<IActionResult> ExportLarge(CancellationToken cancellationToken)
{
    // For long-running generation, honor RequestAborted
    var data = await GenerateReportAsync(cancellationToken);
    var bytes = System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data);
    return File(bytes, "text/csv", "report.csv");
}
```

Note the `CancellationToken` parameter ‚Äî ASP.NET Core automatically binds it to `HttpContext.RequestAborted`, giving you cooperative cancellation if the client disconnects. This replaces the role `Thread.Abort` played in request termination.
